{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> πλόος</b>, ὁ, <br /> <i>Attic dialect</i> <i>contraction</i> <b>πλοῦς;</b> <i>plural</i> πλοῖ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 304, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 5.7.7; _genitive_ πλῶν “OGI” 132.9 (Egypt, 2nd c.BC)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>dative</i> πλοῖς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 5.83; _accusative_ πλοῦς 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Meteorologica” 362b24 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; later, a <i>genitive</i> <i>singular</i> πλοός, as if of third <i>declension</i> (compare χοῦς A), [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Periplus Maris Rubri [1st c.AD]” 62, “OGI” 572.21 (Myra, 2nd-3rd c.AD), 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus Eph.1.14; _dative_ πλοΐ 1st c.BC: Diodorus Siculus Historicus 21.2: _plural_ πλόες 9th c.AD: Photius Legal icographus, etc.; _accusative_ πλόας “IGRom.” 4.841 (from Hierapolis)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: (πλέω):—<b>sailing, voyage,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.169, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus (who always has the _disyllable_ form) 2.29, etc.; ἔσσεται Ἀγεάνακτι καλὸς π. ἐς Μιτυλάναν 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 7.52; ναῶν π. 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 7.32; πλόον ὁρμαίνειν 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” [same place] \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; πλοῦν στεῖλαι, ποιεῖσθαι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 1045, “Ph.” 552 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἔξω πλόου out of <b>one's course,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 11.39; ἐπ᾽ ἡμέρας τέσσερας πλόος 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.29 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; μῆκός ἐστι πλόος ἡμέραι τέσσερες its length is four days' <b>sail,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 158 \">Refs</a>]; ἐκ τῶν πλόων when <b>the voyage</b> is done, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 1.185: _metaphorically_, διὰ τοῦ πλοῦ.. τῆς ζωῆς 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 803b. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <b>time</b> or <b>tide for sailing,</b> ὡραῖος π., εἰαρινὸς π., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 630, 678; καιρὸς καὶ π. 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 1450 (_anapaest meter_)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; π. ἡμῖν ἐγίγνετο, i.e. the wind was fair, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 5.24, compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.137; π. ἐστί τινι 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 899, “IA” 92; παραπεσόντος π. τισί 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 4.57.6 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πλῷ χρήσασθαι to have a <b>fair wind,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.3; πλόον δοκάζων 5th c.BC: Sophron Comicus 52: _plural_, καλλίστοις ἐχρήσαντο πλοῖς 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 5.83. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> proverbial, δεύτερος π. 'the next best way', of those who try another scheme if the first fails (from those who use oars when the wind fails, ὁ δ. π. ἐστι δήπου λεγόμενος, ἂν ἀποτύχῃ τις οὐρίου (conjecture), κώπαισι πλεῖν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Menander Comicus 241), 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 99d, “Phlb.” 19c, “Plt.” 300c \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; δεύτερος δὲ π..., πειρᾶσθαι.. the <b>next best thing</b> is to try.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1284b19; κατὰ τὸν δ. πλοῦν [prev. author] “EN” 1109a35; δ. ἂν εἴη π. τὸ.. 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 8.36.6: proverbial, οὐ παντὸς ἀνδρὸς ἐπὶ τράπεζάν ἐσθ᾽ ὁ π. 4th c.BC(?): Nicolaus Comicus 1.26 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>], compare Κόρινθο; ἡμέτερος ὁ π. 'our innings', [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Comica Adespota” 274. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__4</b></Level3> later, ={ὁδός}, βαιὸν π. αἰὲν ὀκέλλει, of <b>the crawling</b> of